reasoning_messages.content:
To remediate the OpenSCAP finding for configuring OpenSC smart card drivers, the solution ensures that the `/etc/opensc.conf` file contains the `[app default]` section with the `card_drivers` directive set to an empty string. This is achieved by reading the file, processing it with an awk script to guarantee the presence of the section and directive, and writing the result back to the file. The awk script handles cases where the file is missing, empty, or already contains the section and/or directive.

The following tool call executes a bash script that performs these steps:

```bash
run_cmd '
  if [ -f /etc/opensc.conf ]; then
    content=$(cat /etc/opensc.conf)
  else
    content=""
  fi

  processed_content=$(echo "$content" | awk '
    BEGIN { in_section=0; directive_found=0; seen_any_section=0; }
    /^\s*\[app default\]\s*$/ { in_section=1; seen_any_section=1; print; next }
    /^\s*\[\s*[^]]*\s*$/ {
        if (in_section) {
          if (!directive_found) {
            print '\''card_drivers ='\''
          }
          directive_found=0
        }
        seen_any_section=1
        in_section=0
        print
        next
    }
    /^\s*card_drivers\s*=.*$/ {
      if (in_section) {
        directive_found=1
        next
      }
    }
    { print }
    END {
      if (!seen_any_section) {
        print "[app default]"
        print "card_drivers ="
      } else if (in_section && !directive_found) {
        print "card_drivers ="
      }
    }
  ')

  echo "$processed_content" > /etc/opensc.conf
'
```

This single `run_cmd` call encapsulates the entire remediation process, leveraging bash and awk to read, process, and write the configuration file as required.
